Home builder Glenveagh Properties earned almost €46 million last year, turning around a €16 million loss in 2020. Glenveagh said on Tuesday that revenues more than doubled in 2021 to €476.8 million from €232.3 million the previous year. Pre-tax profit hit €45.7 million last year against a €15.7 million loss in 2020. The company built 1,150 new homes in the year, a 47 per cent increase on 2020, despite a Government-imposed 13-week lockdown on construction. During the year Glenveagh agreed to build more than 2,050 homes in partnerships with Dublin City and Fingal County councils. It bought 12 new sites with space for more than 2,700 homes for a total of €72 million. Glenveagh caculates that building costs rose a total of 6 per cent last year, with continued uncertaintly likely in 2022. The group intends to build more than 1,400 homes in 2022, including two forward-funded projects. Stephen Garvey, Glenveagh chief executive, dubbed 2021’s performance “excellent” saying the company grew output by 36 per cent. He added Glenveagh dealt with the “challenges of the pandemic” and remained on course to meet its ambition of building 3,000 homes a year.